StringLiteralExpr.value: MMLDEMO demonstrates the capabilities of the MML function and how to use it.
This demo guides through a number of examples showing the syntactical
variations MML can be used with.
To run properly this demo requires:
1.) Symbolic Math Toolbox 3.0.1 for MATLAB with Maple 8 Kernel or later.
2.) To display the expression in MS Internet Explorer install MATHPLAYER.
[Press any key to continue with Example 1]

[Press any key to continue with Example 2]
A useful feature of MML is the possibility of displaying the current content
of the global variable ANS by simply typing MML.
To demonstrate this we assume that ANS contains i.e. a symbolic matrix.
Now the webbrowser opens and displays the content of ANS, here: the matrix.
This example demonstrates the use of the display options ''type'' and ''nwb''.
Both options can be used in each syntax variation of the MML function.
If MathML code typed in the Command Window is needed in addition to displaying
the term in the webbrowser, the option ''type'' can be used.
Now the webbrowser is opened displaying the term and the corresponding
MathML code is typed in the Command Window.
